<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910802-0081</DOCNO><DOCID>910802-0081.</DOCID><HL>   Consolidated Stores   Says 2nd-Period Net   Will Top Last Year's</HL><DATE>08/02/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5C</SO><CO>   CNS</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)ALL SPECIALTY RETAILERS (RTS)SPECIALTY APPAREL RETAILERS (SAP)</IN><NS>EXCLUSIVE INTERVIEW WITH CHIEF EXECUTIVES (CEO)</NS><RE>DELAWARE (DE)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   COLUMBUS, Ohio -- Consolidated Stores Corp. expects itsfiscal second-quarter net income to beat last year's twocents a share, Chairman William G. Kelley said.   &quot;If we don't, I've done a lousy job,&quot; he said in aninterview. &quot;We intend to grow around here. We feel we have aterrific little niche in specialty stores.&quot;</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Kelley wouldn't offer a specific forecast for thequarter, which will end Monday. Analysts also expect thecompany to exceed its year-earlier net of $804,000 on salesof $159.1 million. For the year-earlier first half,Consolidated posted a net loss of $2.9 million, or six centsa share, on sales of $299.1 million.   Consolidated, which operates 341 closeout retail stores inthe Midwest and Southeast, plans to open 50 more stores thisyear, mostly in its third quarter, Mr. Kelley said. Thecompany also will close about 20 stores during the year.   Capital spending at Consolidated will rise to $18 millionin fiscal 1992, which ends next Feb. 1, from $14 million infiscal 1990. A figure for fiscal 1991 spending wasn'tavailable. The bulk of the spending will be used for storeexpansion.   As part of its growth strategy, Consolidated says it willopen this year about 20 test-market stores called All forOne, which will offer customers lower-priced goods. &quot;We aregoing to grow aggressively but cautiously,&quot; the chairmansaid.   Mr. Kelley said the stores are &quot;important in today'seconomy&quot; and will remain popular even as the country recoversfrom the recession. &quot;For the next 10 years, many Americanconsumers are going to be extremely focused on getting valuefor a dollar,&quot; he said.   Food products as well as health and beauty products areselling &quot;quite well&quot; at Consolidated's Odd Lots and Big Lotsstores, Mr. Kelley said.   The stores are also promoting more automotive, hardwareand sporting goods products to try to draw more malecustomers. Two years ago, men accounted for just 25% of allshoppers in the stores. &quot;We have a strong mission to do atleast 40% of our business with the male shopper,&quot; Mr. Kelleysaid.</TEXT></DOC>